      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — ~ 6–8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920 × 1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Clean gym or indoor-home-gym lighting; neutral background or subtle gym-floor backdrop; soft key-light + ambient fill so shoulder, arm path, and posture are clearly visible\n* Sound: Soft ambient (dumbbell movement, subtle breathing, minimal noise), no voice-over (optionally gentle inhale-exhale cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Open floor space or gym area with free weights (dumbbells or barbell). Enough room to lift arms forward without obstruction.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) capturing head to feet — showing upright posture, arm raise arc, shoulder level, foot stance.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, in workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts/pants), holding dumbbells (or barbell) at sides in starting position, ready to raise.\nAction / Beats (0s–8s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup: Stand with feet about shoulder- or hip-width apart, knees slightly bent/soft, spine neutral, chest up, core engaged. Dumbbells (or barbell) start at front of thighs, arms relaxed, palms facing body (or down if pronated).\n* 1–2 s — Brace & prepare: Shoulders back and down (not shrugged), maintain posture and avoid momentum. Slight bend in elbows to reduce joint stress; focus on stability and control.\n* 2–4 s — Raise / Concentric Phase: Exhale; lift the weights straight out in front of you in a smooth controlled arc until arms reach about shoulder height (parallel to floor). Keep torso still — do not use legs or back to swing.\n* 4–5 s — Hold / Peak: Pause briefly (~0.2–0.5 s) at the top—arms horizontal, shoulders activated (especially the front deltoids). This helps maximize muscle tension and control.\n* 5–7 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly lower the weights back to front-thigh position under control. Avoid dropping or using momentum; maintain posture and tension.\n* 7–8 s — Reset / Ready: Arms relaxed, posture upright, core engaged — ready for next rep or fade-out.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Front (anterior) deltoids — responsible for shoulder flexion and raising the arms forward.\n* Secondary / Supporting: Slight involvement of lateral deltoids, upper chest (clavicular portion of pectoralis major), trapezius / upper-back stabilizers, forearms (grip), and core (for stability).\nBenefits & Why Use Front Raise\n* Good for isolating the front shoulder (anterior deltoids) — helps build definition and strength in front-shoulder area that compound lifts (presses/bench) might not target as directly.\n* Improves shoulder strength and mobility — useful for functional movements that require lifting or reaching forward.\n* Can complement other shoulder/upper-body exercises — helps balance shoulder development and avoid over-reliance on pressing movements.\n* Isolation-style finish or accessory exercise — suitable after heavy compound lifts to further stimulate shoulders without heavy joint load.\nForm & Safety / Technique Notes\n* Use light to moderate weights — heavy loads often lead to using momentum (swinging) or compensation (back/legs), reducing effectiveness and risking injury.\n* Maintain neutral spine, stable core, and upright posture — avoid leaning back or using lower-back/hip momentum.\n* Keep elbows slightly bent — helps protect shoulder joints and keeps tension on deltoids.\n* Raise only to shoulder height (parallel to floor) — going higher may shift stress to other structures or reduce effectiveness on anterior deltoids.\n* Control both concentric (up) and eccentric (down) phases — avoid bouncing or letting weights drop. Smooth motion leads to better muscle engagement.",
