      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — ~ 7–8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym-style lighting (cable machine visible, neutral or slightly dark background to isolate the motion), subject in standard workout clothes; soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight side deltoid, arm movement, and cable path\n* Sound: Soft ambient (cable pulley/weight stack noise, subtle foot/shoe stir, controlled breathing), no voice-over (or optionally subtle inhale/exhale cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: A gym cable-pulley machine — pulley lowered to near floor/hip level, single-handle attachment ready, adequate clearance for arm-path. Floor and background clear.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or waist-height), capturing from head to hips/feet — so that shoulder, torso, cable, and arm motion are visible. This ensures path of raise, posture, and shoulder alignment are clear.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + gym pants/shorts), standing sideways to cable stack, ready to perform raise.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Grip: Pulley set low (near floor), subject stands sideways to stack (e.g. right shoulder toward cable for left-arm raise). Grasp handle with working arm, arm hanging down, wrist neutral, elbow soft-bent. Feet shoulder-width, knees slightly bent, core engaged, chest up.\n* 1–2 s — Brace / Prepare: Retract and depress shoulders (shoulders pulled slightly down/back), avoid shrugging; brace core and glutes; maintain upright posture, minimal torso sway.\n* 2–4 s — Raise / Concentric Phase: Exhale; raise the handle outward and upward laterally — lead with your elbow (not hand) — until your arm (elbow) reaches shoulder-height (arm roughly parallel to floor). Slight bend maintained in elbow. Keep movement controlled, avoid swinging or jerking.\n* 4–5 s — Peak / Hold: Brief pause (≈ 0.2–0.5 s) at top — maintain tension in side deltoid (medial deltoid), shoulder stable, no trap shrug.\n* 5–7 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly lower the handle back to start under control, resisting gravity; don’t drop fast — maintain posture, core braced.\n* 7–8 s — Reset / Ready: Arm down, body stable; ready for next rep or end clip.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\n* Medial Deltoid (side head of shoulder): Main target — responsible for shoulder abduction (lifting arm to the side), giving shoulder width/“caps.”\n* Supporting muscles: Assistive roles from upper-back stabilizers (trapezius, rotator-cuff muscles) for shoulder stability, and core / trunk stabilizers to maintain posture and prevent torso sway during lift.\nWhy Cable Lateral Raise — Benefits\n* Constant tension through full range of motion: Unlike free weights (dumbbells), cable resistance keeps the deltoid under load from bottom to top — no “resting” at bottom, better for hypertrophy.\n* Improved shoulder shape and width: Specifically develops the medial deltoid, contributing to broader shoulders and better upper-body proportions.\n* Better control and isolation: Cable setup reduces momentum or swing, allowing strict form — good for isolating deltoid rather than relying on traps or momentum.\n* Versatility: You can easily adjust cable height, attachment type, single-arm vs. bilateral, and rep tempo to target shoulder in different angles and with varied stimulus.\nForm & Safety / Key Technique Tips\n* Keep slight bend in elbow throughout — straight-arm may increase stress on shoulder joint.\n* Lead the movement with elbow, not hand — ensures load stays on the deltoid rather than transferring to traps or forearm.\n* Avoid shrugging — shoulders should remain down and back; shrugging shifts work to traps.\n* Use light to moderate weight — because it's isolation with small muscles, heavy loads often cause compensation or form breakdown.\n* Maintain core tightness and upright torso, avoid leaning or using momentum; controlled movement both up and down maximizes muscle engagement and minimizes injury risk.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "* Medial Deltoid (side head of shoulder): Main target — responsible for shoulder abduction (lifting arm to the side), giving shoulder width/“caps.”\n* Supporting muscles: Assistive roles from upper-back stabilizers (trapezius, rotator-cuff muscles) for shoulder stability, and core / trunk stabilizers to maintain posture and prevent torso sway during lift.\nWhy Cable Lateral Raise —",
      "benefits": "* Constant tension through full range of motion: Unlike free weights (dumbbells), cable resistance keeps the deltoid under load from bottom to top — no “resting” at bottom, better for hypertrophy.\n* Improved shoulder shape and width: Specifically develops the medial deltoid, contributing to broader shoulders and better upper-body proportions.\n* Better control and isolation: Cable setup reduces momentum or swing, allowing strict form — good for isolating deltoid rather than relying on traps or momentum.\n* Versatility: You can easily adjust cable height, attachment type, single-arm vs. bilateral, and rep tempo to target shoulder in different angles and with varied stimulus.",
