      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — about 7–9 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym-style lighting or clean indoor lighting; neutral or dark background helps focus on shoulder/arm movement. Subject wears standard workout clothes; soft key light + ambient fill to highlight arms, shoulder blade motion, and posture.\n* Sound: Ambient gym noise (light dumbbell contact/clink, subtle movement, breathing), no voice-over — optionally subtle inhale/exhale cues.\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym or home-gym with dumbbells (or light weights). For best isolation: flat floor or slight forward-bend setup; optionally bench (incline or chest-supported) if doing supported variation.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) capturing from head to hips — so you see upper back, shoulder blades, arms movement, and torso posture.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or typical build, wearing gym attire (tank/tee + shorts/training pants), holding dumbbells by sides (or ready on bench) — ready to perform raise.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8/9 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup: Stand with feet roughly shoulder-width apart (or slight bend in knees), hinge forward at hips (torso forward, near parallel, or slight angle depending on variant), back neutral, core engaged. Dumbbells hang naturally below chest/abdomen, arms relaxed, elbows slightly bent. Shoulders pulled down and back (no shrug).\n* 1–2 s — Brace & prepare: Engage rear-shoulder and upper-back muscles (scapula retracted slightly), maintain spine neutrality, avoid letting lower back take over.\n* 2–4 s — Raise / Concentric Phase: Exhale; lift dumbbells outward and slightly backward — pulling arms to the side/out-back so they move roughly horizontal to floor — until upper arms are parallel with ground (or slightly below shoulder line). Elbows stay soft (slight bend), wrists neutral, movement controlled. At top, squeeze shoulder blades together (retraction) to maximize posterior deltoid and upper-back activation.\n* 4–5 s — Peak / Hold: Pause ~0.2–0.5 s at top — feel contraction in rear delts (posterior shoulder) and upper-back stabilizers (rhomboids, mid-traps).\n* 5–7 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly lower dumbbells back to starting position, under control — do not let them drop quickly. Keep torso and back stable.\n* 7–8/9 s — Reset / Ready: Arms down, torso steady, shoulders relaxed — ready for next rep or end clip.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\n* Posterior deltoid (rear delts): Main target — responsible for scapular retraction and shoulder extension/back-pull.\n* Supporting / stabilizing muscles: Upper-back muscles, especially rhomboids and middle/lower trapezius, help retract and stabilize the shoulder blades. Rotator-cuff muscles assist in shoulder joint control.\nBenefits & Why Use Rear Delt Raise\n* Enhances shoulder balance and symmetry — many workouts over-emphasize front/side delts; targeting rear delts helps round out shoulder musculature for better overall appearance.\n* Improves posture — strong rear delts and upper-back muscles help keep shoulders retracted and prevent slouching/rounded-shoulder posture common with desk work or push-heavy routines.\n* Supports shoulder stability & health — rear delts contribute to shoulder blade control, joint stability, and reduce injury risk, especially in pushing/pulling movements.\n* Useful as isolation exercise / finisher — because it isolates posterior delts and upper-back stabilizers, good for finishing shoulder/back workouts or correcting muscle imbalances.\nForm & Safety / Key Technique & Common Mistakes\n* Use light to moderate weight, especially when starting — rear delts are relatively small muscles; heavy weights often lead to momentum, shrinking isolation benefit and risking shoulder/back strain.\n* Maintain a slight bend in elbows — helps reduce joint stress and keeps tension on delts rather than arms or traps.\n* Torso stable, neutral spine — avoid excessive arching or rounding of back; hinge correctly at hips if bent-over variation.\n* Avoid using momentum or swinging — control the lift up and lowering down for best muscle activation and safety.\n* Scapular control — focus on pulling shoulder blades together (retraction) at top, rather than just lifting arms; this emphasizes rear delts and prevents overuse of traps.",
