      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — approximately 7–9 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym-style or plain indoor lighting; background simple/neutral so focus stays on body posture, arms, cable/rope, and motion. Soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight shoulder/upper-back region clearly.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (cable/rope movement sound, subtle foot contact, breathing), no narration (or optionally subtle breath-in / breath-out cues).\nScene Setup\n* Location: Cable-pulley machine (single-tower or dual) in gym — rope attachment on pulley set at about head/upper-chest height (slightly above eye level). Ensure floor space in front of machine is clear.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) capturing full upper body (head to waist + arms), cable/rope, and body posture — enough to see elbow path, shoulder blades, and cable path.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing workout attire; standing facing the cable machine, feet shoulder-width (or slight staggered), ready to perform the movement.\nAction / Beats (0 s–~8 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position: Subject stands facing the cable machine, feet about shoulder-width apart (or slight stagger for stability). Grasp rope-handles with both hands (neutral grip — palms facing each other), arms extended forward at chest/shoulder height. Slight backward lean (≈ 20°) so tension is on cable, core engaged, shoulders relaxed / slightly rounded forward.\n* 1–2 s — Brace / Prepare: Brace core and glutes, keep spine neutral, shoulders not shrugged. Prepare to pull by setting scapula (shoulder-blades) ready to retract.\n* 2–4 s — Pull / Concentric Phase: Exhale; pull the rope toward your face — drive elbows up and out (flared wide), so upper arms end roughly parallel to floor, hands near or slightly above ears / forehead level. Simultaneously externally rotate shoulders (thumbs pointing backward or slightly upward) so elbows drive outward and backwards — this emphasizes rear delts and rotator-cuff activation.\n* 4–5 s — Peak / Hold & Squeeze: Pause ~0.2–0.5 s — squeeze shoulder-blades together; emphasize engagement of rear delts, traps, rhomboids. Torso stable, core tight.\n* 5–7 s — Return / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly extend arms forward, controlling the cable back to start — avoid letting shoulders collapse forward or using momentum. Maintain posture, core engaged.\n* 7–8/9 s — Reset / Ready: Arms extended forward, body stable, prepare for next rep or fade-out.\nMuscles / Focus (What Face Pull Works)\nFace pulls target several muscles of the upper back, shoulder girdle, and rotator cuff.\n* Primary / Key Targets:\n\n* Posterior (rear) deltoids — primary shoulder-extension / abduction action at rear of delts.\n* Upper-back / scapular muscles: including trapezius (mid & lower fibers) and rhomboids — for scapular retraction and stability.\n* Rotator-cuff external rotators (muscles like infraspinatus, teres minor) — the external-rotation component of the pull works these, aiding shoulder joint health.\n* Secondary / Stabilizing Muscles:\n\n* Core and lower-back (isometric) — to maintain posture and stability during pull.\n* Arms / biceps (to some degree) — because elbow flexion contributes, though the focus should not shift to arms.\nBenefits & Why Use Face Pull\n* Balanced shoulder & upper-back development: Face pulls strengthen rear delts and upper-back muscles often neglected by pressing-heavy routines — helps build balanced musculature, avoid “front-heavy” shoulders.\n* Shoulder health, stability & posture: Regular face pulls help improve scapular stability and shoulder joint integrity; beneficial especially if you perform a lot of overhead pressing or pushing.\n* Improved posture / counter to forward-shoulder rounding: Because of scapular retraction and rear-deltoid activation, face pulls help undo forward-rounded posture common in sedentary or desk-bound people.\n* Great warm-up / “pre-hab” exercise: Light face-pull sets before pressing or pulling workouts can pre-activate stabilizers, prepare shoulder girdle, and reduce injury risk.\nForm & Safety / Key Technique Tips\n* Use a rope attachment on a cable machine, with pulley set at about head or upper-chest height (not extremely high or low) — correct anchor point ensures proper shoulder mechanics.\n* Use a neutral (palms-facing) grip, thumbs preferably pointing backward — this helps external-rotation and reduces internal rotation stress on shoulders.\n* Lead with elbows, not hands — elbows should flair outward and slightly up; hands follow — ensures the rear delts and scapular muscles drive the motion, not biceps or forearms.\n* Avoid heavy weights that force momentum or swinging — use light to moderate load; movement should be smooth and controlled, both on the pull and return, to maximize muscle activation and maintain safety.\n* Keep core and glutes engaged, torso stable — avoid leaning or arching the back during the pull.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
