      "category": "shoulders",
      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — approximately 7–9 seconds long.\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps.\n* Lighting & Color: Gym-style or clean indoor lighting; neutral background (gym bench, floor, wall) to keep focus on subject; soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight shoulder/arm movement, dumbbells, and posture.\n* Sound: Soft ambient gym noise (subtle metal/dumbbell sound, slight floor or bench creak, breathing), no voice-over (or optional faint inhale-exhale cues).\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym or home-gym with a bench (with back support, upright) and dumbbells. Floor space clear around bench.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or at waist level), capturing from head to feet — to include bench, back support, dumbbells, and full upper-body posture. This ensures you see starting position, torso alignment, shoulder/arm path, and end range.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts or pants), seated upright on bench with back pressed against backrest, dumbbells in hand, ready for press.\nAction / Beats (0 s–≈ 9 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position: Subject sits upright on bench, back firmly against back-pad. Feet flat on floor, shoulder-width apart, knees bent, core slightly braced. Dumbbells held at shoulder height — elbows slightly forward of body (not flared completely sideways), palms facing forward or slightly inward (neutral or slight rotation), wrists aligned, dumbbells resting near shoulders. Chest up, shoulder blades retracted/stable.\n* 1–2 s — Brace / Prepare: Take a deep breath, engage core and glutes (“brace”), ensure torso is stable and upright, back pressed against bench, stable foot contact. Shoulders pulled slightly down/back to avoid shrugging.\n* 2–4 s — Press / Concentric Phase: Exhale; press both dumbbells upward in a controlled motion — arms extend overhead or slightly in front (depending on comfort and shoulder mobility). Keep elbows tracking upward, dumbbells moving in a smooth path, avoid arching lower back or excessive torso lean.\n* 4–5 s — Top / Lockout / Hold: At full (or near-full) extension, pause ~0.2–0.5 s — arms almost extended (elbows maybe slightly bent), shoulders stable, dumbbells overhead or slightly behind forehead depending on range, spine neutral. This is the “peak contraction.”\n* 5–7 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly lower dumbbells back to shoulder-level starting position under control (no dropping), keeping back against bench, core braced, elbows under wrists. Avoid letting shoulders collapse or back arch.\n* 7–9 s — Reset / Prepare for Next Rep: Return fully to start position — dumbbells at shoulders, posture stable, ready for next rep or fade out.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus (What the Exercise Works)\n* Anterior (front) deltoids: Primary movers during upward press — responsible for lifting arms overhead.\n* Lateral (side) deltoids: Assist in stabilization and contribute to shoulder width; dumbbell variation allows better activation compared to some fixed-path lifts.\n* Triceps: Assist in elbow extension at the top of press, helping lock out the movement.\n* Upper trapezius & upper-back stabilizers: Help stabilize shoulder girdle and maintain posture under load.\n* Core & spine stabilizers: Although seated, core engagement helps maintain spine neutrality, preventing excessive lumbar arch.\nWhy Use Seated Dumbbell Press — Key Benefits\n* Better shoulder isolation: Sitting with back support reduces lower-body and core stabilization demands, letting shoulders (deltoids) do the bulk of the work — effective for targeting shoulder strength/hypertrophy.\n* Reduced risk for lower-back stress: Because back is supported and you are not standing, the risk of lumbar strain is lower than standing overhead presses — helpful if you have back issues or want to focus on shoulder work.\n* Better for strict form & control: Dumbbells allow independent arm movement — helps address left-right imbalances, ensures even development, and improves shoulder mobility and control.\n* Versatility & suitability for many levels: Easy to set up, suitable for beginners to advanced lifters, or for heavier load without complex stabilization, making it a staple in shoulder or upper-body routines.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Ensure back fully supported — sit firmly on bench with back against pad; avoid arching lower back during press. Core and glutes braced.\n* Elbow path and angle: Keep elbows slightly forward (about 45° from torso), avoid flaring wide out sideways — helps reduce shoulder joint stress.\n* Use controlled motion — both upward (press) and downward (lower) phases should be smooth and deliberate; avoid using momentum or “jerking” the weights.\n* Moderate weight — especially when starting; too heavy dumbbells often lead to form breakdown or stress on shoulders/elbows.\n* Breathing & brace: Exhale during press upward; inhale during lowering. Keep chest up, scapula stable, core tight.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "(What the Exercise Works)\n* Anterior (front) deltoids: Primary movers during upward press — responsible for lifting arms overhead.\n* Lateral (side) deltoids: Assist in stabilization and contribute to shoulder width; dumbbell variation allows better activation compared to some fixed-path lifts.\n* Triceps: Assist in elbow extension at the top of press, helping lock out the movement.\n* Upper trapezius & upper-back stabilizers: Help stabilize shoulder girdle and maintain posture under load.\n* Core & spine stabilizers: Although seated, core engagement helps maintain spine neutrality, preventing excessive lumbar arch.",
      "benefits": "Seated Dumbbell Press — Key Benefits\n* Better shoulder isolation: Sitting with back support reduces lower-body and core stabilization demands, letting shoulders (deltoids) do the bulk of the work — effective for targeting shoulder strength/hypertrophy.\n* Reduced risk for lower-back stress: Because back is supported and you are not standing, the risk of lumbar strain is lower than standing overhead presses — helpful if you have back issues or want to focus on shoulder work.\n* Better for strict form & control: Dumbbells allow independent arm movement — helps address left-right imbalances, ensures even development, and improves shoulder mobility and control.\n* Versatility & suitability for many levels: Easy to set up, suitable for beginners to advanced lifters, or for heavier load without complex stabilization, making it a staple in shoulder or upper-body routines.",
      "safety": "/ Technique Tips\n* Ensure back fully supported — sit firmly on bench with back against pad; avoid arching lower back during press. Core and glutes braced.\n* Elbow path and angle: Keep elbows slightly forward (about 45° from torso), avoid flaring wide out sideways — helps reduce shoulder joint stress.\n* Use controlled motion — both upward (press) and downward (lower) phases should be smooth and deliberate; avoid using momentum or “jerking” the weights.\n* Moderate weight — especially when starting; too heavy dumbbells often lead to form breakdown or stress on shoulders/elbows.\n* Breathing & brace: Exhale during press upward; inhale during lowering. Keep chest up, scapula stable, core tight."
