      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — ~ 7–9 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym or home-gym lighting (clean background, neutral floor/bench), with soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight shoulders, torso alignment, dumbbell path.\n* Sound: Ambient (dumbbell weight shift, subtle foot contact, breathing), no voice-over (or optional soft breath-in/exhale cues).\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym floor or home-gym space; free-weight dumbbell in hand; floor clear for stable stance.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or waist height) capturing head to feet — so you see stance, torso alignment, arm path, and balance.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts/pants), holding a dumbbell in one hand at shoulder height, ready to press.\nAction / Beats (0 s–~8–9 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position: Stand with feet about shoulder-width apart (or hip-width), dumbbell held at shoulder height in one hand (elbow bent, palm forward or slightly rotated), non-working hand relaxed or on hip for balance. Core engaged, spine neutral, shoulders stable.\n* 1–2 s — Brace & Prepare: Brace core and glutes; keep torso upright; ensure wrist above elbow and elbow above shoulder in vertical alignment; prevent leaning or twisting.\n* 2–4 s — Press / Concentric Phase: Exhale; press dumbbell straight overhead until arm is fully (or nearly fully) extended — the dumbbell should travel in a vertical path, with shoulder, elbow and wrist stacked. Avoid arching lower back or shifting hips.\n* 4–5 s — Lockout / Peak Hold: Slight pause (≈ 0.2–0.5 s) at top — full extension, shoulder stable, arm straight (elbow perhaps slightly soft), core tight, torso still.\n* 5–7 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly lower dumbbell under control back to shoulder-height starting position — avoid dropping or using momentum, maintain alignment and balance.\n* 7–8/9 s — Reset / Ready: Return to upright stance, dumbbell at shoulder height, posture stable — ready for next rep or clip end.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\n* Deltoids (anterior + medial heads): primary movers — pressing overhead works both front and side shoulder heads.\n* Triceps: contribute for elbow extension during the press.\n* Stabilizing muscles: Because load is unilateral, the exercise engages core muscles (obliques, transverse abdominis, spinal stabilizers) to prevent torso rotation or lateral bend; also upper-back / shoulder-stabilizing muscles (e.g. rotator-cuff, traps) help maintain posture & joint integrity.\nBenefits & Why Use It\n* Allows unilateral training — helps identify and correct strength/muscle-imbalances between left and right shoulders.\n* Enhances shoulder strength, mobility, stability and overhead pressing power, while minimizing demands on symmetry or barbell-setup.\n* Promotes core and torso stability — unilateral load forces core & spinal stabilizers to engage, which aids posture, balance and functional strength.\n* Useful as accessory or main lift — can serve as an alternative to bilateral presses for those with shoulder mobility issues or for those wanting balanced shoulder development.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Keep spine neutral, core tight, glutes braced, avoid overarching lower back.\n* Press vertically, with wrist–elbow–shoulder aligned — don’t let elbow drift too far forward or let the weight arc outward.\n* Use moderate weight — small imbalance or instability with heavy load can strain shoulder or spine; ensure control over full range.\n* Maintain smooth, controlled motion — both upward (press) and downward (lower) phases; avoid momentum or jerky moves.",
