      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional clip — about 7–9 seconds total\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Plain indoor floor (home-gym or clean room), neutral background; neutral floor, workout-clothes; soft key light + ambient fill so shoulder/arm motion and posture are clear.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (band stretch/rubber noise, subtle breathing, minimal background distractions), no spoken commentary (optional gentle breath-in / breath-out cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Home or gym floor; a resistance band with handles (or loop band) placed under feet. Enough vertical clearance overhead. Floor clear of obstacles.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral), capturing full body from head to feet — so foot placement, body posture, arm motion, and band tension are visible.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult female, average/athletic build, wearing workout clothes (t-shirt or tank + shorts/pants), standing with band under feet, ready to press.\nAction / Beats (0–~9 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup: Stand upright, feet about shoulder-width apart, the middle of resistance band securely under feet; hold handles or ends of band such that hands are at shoulder height, elbows bent, palms forward (or neutral). Core engaged, spine neutral.\n* 1–2 s — Brace / Prepare: Slight soft-bend in knees, glutes and core braced, shoulders back/down (not shrugged), band taut, ready to press.\n* 2–4 s — Press / Concentric Phase: Exhale; press band overhead — extend arms upward so hands move straight up (vertical path), fully or near-fully extend elbows and shoulders while keeping torso stable. Band should stretch as you ascend.\n* 4–5 s — Peak / Hold: Pause ~0.2-0.5 s at the top — arms extended overhead (without locking joints harshly), shoulder blades stable, body upright, band stretched, showing full extension.\n* 5–7 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly lower arms back down to shoulder-height starting position, controlling band tension — avoid letting band snap back; maintain posture, core engaged.\n* 7–9 s — Reset / Ready: Arms at start position, posture stable, ready for next rep or fade-out.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\n* Deltoids (shoulders): All heads — especially anterior (front) and medial (side) delts — as you press overhead.\n* Triceps: Assist in elbow extension during overhead press.\n* Core & stabilizers: Since you’re standing and balancing against band tension, core (abs, lower back) and stabilizing muscles help maintain posture and control.\nBenefits & Why Use Resistance-Band Shoulder Press\n* Good for home- or travel-friendly workouts — you just need a resistance band and a small clear space; no heavy equipment required.\n* Offers variable, accommodating resistance — band tension increases as you stretch it, challenging muscles through full range of motion and often keeping tension even at the top of the movement, unlike free weights where gravity may reduce tension near lockout.\n* Gentle on joints & connective tissue, while still effective — beneficial especially if you have shoulder mobility issues, are rehabbing, or want a lighter alternative to heavy overhead press.\n* Helps build shoulder strength, stability, and muscle balance — pushing overhead from a band forces stabilizers to engage, improving shoulder health and mobility alongside strength.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Keep spine neutral and core tight, avoid overarching lower back when pressing overhead — prevents lumbar strain.\n* Use a band of appropriate resistance — not too slack (or you’ll lose tension), not too stiff (or form may break). Adjust band length or step harder on the band to modulate resistance.\n* Press in a vertical path — hands go straight up; avoid pushing forward or backward which may transfer stress to other joints.\n* Control both upward and downward phases — no abrupt or jerky motions, avoid letting band snap you up or down; smooth, controlled reps maximize muscle activation and minimize injury risk.\n* Maintain shoulder-blades stable (not shrugged) — keep shoulders down and back; proper scapular positioning helps shoulder health and ensures the delts and triceps do the work.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult female, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "* Deltoids (shoulders): All heads — especially anterior (front) and medial (side) delts — as you press overhead.\n* Triceps: Assist in elbow extension during overhead press.\n* Core & stabilizers: Since you’re standing and balancing against band tension, core (abs, lower back) and stabilizing muscles help maintain posture and control.",
      "benefits": "& Why Use Resistance-Band Shoulder Press\n* Good for home- or travel-friendly workouts — you just need a resistance band and a small clear space; no heavy equipment required.\n* Offers variable, accommodating resistance — band tension increases as you stretch it, challenging muscles through full range of motion and often keeping tension even at the top of the movement, unlike free weights where gravity may reduce tension near lockout.\n* Gentle on joints & connective tissue, while still effective — beneficial especially if you have shoulder mobility issues, are rehabbing, or want a lighter alternative to heavy overhead press.\n* Helps build shoulder strength, stability, and muscle balance — pushing overhead from a band forces stabilizers to engage, improving shoulder health and mobility alongside strength.",
      "safety": "/ Technique Tips\n* Keep spine neutral and core tight, avoid overarching lower back when pressing overhead — prevents lumbar strain.\n* Use a band of appropriate resistance — not too slack (or you’ll lose tension), not too stiff (or form may break). Adjust band length or step harder on the band to modulate resistance.\n* Press in a vertical path — hands go straight up; avoid pushing forward or backward which may transfer stress to other joints.\n* Control both upward and downward phases — no abrupt or jerky motions, avoid letting band snap you up or down; smooth, controlled reps maximize muscle activation and minimize injury risk.\n* Maintain shoulder-blades stable (not shrugged) — keep shoulders down and back; proper scapular positioning helps shoulder health and ensures the delts and triceps do the work."
