      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional clip — ~ 6–8 seconds long.\n* Resolution: 1920 × 1080 (Full HD), 24 fps.\n* Lighting & Color: Neutral indoor or gym lighting; background simple/clean (empty floor, plain wall or minimal gym background) to highlight arm motion and posture.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (breathing, slight air/body movement), no voice-over (or optional soft inhale/exhale cues).\nScene Setup\n* Location: Any open floor space — home, gym, corridor, open room. No equipment needed.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or neutral) capturing full body head-to-toes — to show arms, torso, and stance clearly.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, standing upright, wearing workout clothes (t-shirt/vest + shorts or pants), arms at sides initially.\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup: Subject stands with feet shoulder-width apart, spine neutral, core slightly braced, posture upright, arms relaxed at sides.\n* 1–2 s — Raise Arms: Slowly raise both arms out to the sides, keeping them extended straight (or with minimal bend), until arms are roughly parallel to the floor (forming a “T”-shape with body).\n* 2–4 s — Begin Circles (Forward): Move the arms forward in small, controlled circular motions (start small). Focus on rotating through the shoulders, not swinging with momentum. Exhale as movement begins.\n* 4–5 s — Gradually Expand Circles / Maintain Motion: Optionally increase the size of the circles gradually as comfort allows; maintain steady rhythm.\n* 5–6 s — Reverse Direction: After a few seconds, reverse the circle direction (backward / counter-clockwise) — inhale during this transition or as you reverse.\n* 6–7 s — Slow Down / Return Arms: After completing forward & backward rotations, lower arms gently back to sides, return posture to upright, ready to end or repeat.\n* 7–8 s — End / Reset: Reset stance, relax arms, core stable — ready for next movement or fade-out.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\nArm Circles primarily focus on mobility, activation, and light endurance in the upper-body region. Key muscles and areas involved:\n* Shoulders (deltoids): Front, middle, and rear deltoid involvement as shoulders rotate and arms move.\n* Upper back & scapular stabilizers: Muscles around shoulder blades (upper-back, scapula stabilizers) engage, improving posture, shoulder stability, and mobility.\n* Arms (biceps/triceps) & upper arm muscles: Light isometric engagement during motion helps keep arms stable, aiding endurance.\n* Joint mobility & connective tissue (shoulder, rotator-cuff, ligaments): The circular motion helps lubricate shoulder joints, increase blood flow, and improve flexibility — useful for warm-ups or recovery.\nBenefits & Why Use Arm Circles\n* Easy warm-up or mobility primer: Great to loosen up shoulders, upper back and arms before heavier workouts or after long periods of inactivity.\n* Increases blood flow & shoulder joint lubrication, preparing muscles, tendons and ligaments for activity, reducing injury risk.\n* Improves shoulder and upper-back mobility and posture, which helps counteract stiffness from desk work or lack of movement.\n* No equipment, anywhere-friendly — can be done at home, office, outdoors; minimal space required.\n* Light activation and endurance — good for rehabilitation, warm-up, or as a “movement snack” to break long sedentary periods.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Keep arms extended (or minimal bend), and torso upright, spine neutral — don’t arch your lower back or lean to compensate.\n* Use controlled motion, avoid jerky or overly fast circles — smooth movement ensures muscle/connective-tissue benefit and reduces stress on joints.\n* Vary circle size: start small when warming up, then gradually increase radius as range of motion improves — helps gradually mobilize shoulders.\n* Focus on shoulder joint, not swinging arms from torso or using momentum — aim for shoulder-controlled motion rather than using body sway or momentum.\n* Reverse direction after forward circles — ensures balanced joint mobility and avoids overworking one direction",
