      "muscles": "Arm Circles primarily focus on mobility, activation, and light endurance in the upper-body region. Key muscles and areas involved:\n* Shoulders (deltoids): Front, middle, and rear deltoid involvement as shoulders rotate and arms move.\n* Upper back & scapular stabilizers: Muscles around shoulder blades (upper-back, scapula stabilizers) engage, improving posture, shoulder stability, and mobility.\n* Arms (biceps/triceps) & upper arm muscles: Light isometric engagement during motion helps keep arms stable, aiding endurance.\n* Joint mobility & connective tissue (shoulder, rotator-cuff, ligaments): The circular motion helps lubricate shoulder joints, increase blood flow, and improve flexibility — useful for warm-ups or recovery.",
      "benefits": "& Why Use Arm Circles\n* Easy warm-up or mobility primer: Great to loosen up shoulders, upper back and arms before heavier workouts or after long periods of inactivity.\n* Increases blood flow & shoulder joint lubrication, preparing muscles, tendons and ligaments for activity, reducing injury risk.\n* Improves shoulder and upper-back mobility and posture, which helps counteract stiffness from desk work or lack of movement.\n* No equipment, anywhere-friendly — can be done at home, office, outdoors; minimal space required.\n* Light activation and endurance — good for rehabilitation, warm-up, or as a “movement snack” to break long sedentary periods.",
      "safety": "/ Technique Tips\n* Keep arms extended (or minimal bend), and torso upright, spine neutral — don’t arch your lower back or lean to compensate.\n* Use controlled motion, avoid jerky or overly fast circles — smooth movement ensures muscle/connective-tissue benefit and reduces stress on joints.\n* Vary circle size: start small when warming up, then gradually increase radius as range of motion improves — helps gradually mobilize shoulders.\n* Focus on shoulder joint, not swinging arms from torso or using momentum — aim for shoulder-controlled motion rather than using body sway or momentum.\n* Reverse direction after forward circles — ensures balanced joint mobility and avoids overworking one direction"
