      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional clip — ~ 7–9 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Gym environment or clean home-gym setting; neutral background; soft key-light + ambient fill to highlight shoulder, arm path, machine handles.\n* Sound: Soft ambient (machine movement, seat/weight stack noise, subtle breathing), no voice-over (or optional soft inhale/exhale cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Gym, using a shoulder lateral-raise machine (seat + handles + weight stack) — ensure floor around machine is clear; seat adjusted properly for user’s height.\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or at torso-height) capturing from head to waist/hips — so arms, handles, torso posture, and seat back are visible.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + gym pants), seated on the machine with back firmly against the pad, ready to perform raise.\nAction / Beats (0 s–~9 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position: Subject sits upright with back firmly pressed against seat-pad, feet flat on floor, core engaged. Hands grasp handles (or rest forearms if pad-style machine), arms down by sides (or slightly forward depending on machine), shoulders relaxed (not shrugged). Seat height adjusted so handles/arms start at low position.\n* 1–2 s — Brace & Prepare: Engage core and scapular muscles (pull shoulder-blades slightly back/down), ensure spine is neutral, avoid leaning or arching back. Shoulders down, ready to raise.\n* 2–4 s — Raise / Concentric Phase: Exhale; press or lift handles outward and upward laterally — arms move away from body, raising to approximately side-level (shoulder height), in smooth controlled motion. Depending on machine type, movement may involve pushing with handles or lifting arms.\n* 4–5 s — Peak / Hold: Pause ~ 0.2–0.5 s at top — arms approximately parallel to floor, mid-deltoids contracted, shoulders stable. Squeeze delts to maximize contraction.\n* 5–7 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; slowly lower arms/handles back to starting position under control — avoid letting weight stack drop or using momentum. Keep back pressed to pad, core engaged.\n* 7–9 s — Reset / Ready: Arms return to start, posture stable, ready for next rep or fade-out.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus\n* Main target: The medial (lateral) head of the deltoid — responsible for abduction (lifting arms sideways), giving shoulder width/“cap” appearance.\n* Secondary / Supporting muscles: Anterior & posterior deltoid heads (to stabilize), upper-back stabilizers including trapezius and shoulder-blade muscles, and; rotator-cuff / scapular stabilizers to maintain shoulder alignment.\nBenefits & Why Use Machine Lateral Raise\n* Strict isolation & form control: Since the machine stabilizes your posture and guides the motion, it reduces momentum and ensures that deltoids (not traps or momentum) do most of the work. Ideal for shoulder-width / shape routines.\n* Good for beginners or form-focused lifters: Easier to control than free weights (dumbbells), reduces technique demands — seat-pad and guided path make execution simpler and safer.\n* Constant tension through full range: Machine keeps load more consistent across movement, helping with hypertrophy and shoulder muscle activation.\n* Less involvement of stabilizers/back, more focus on delts: Because torso/back is supported, lower-body and core demand is reduced, letting shoulders take primary load — useful when wanting to isolate shoulders or if back/spine recovery is a concern.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Adjust seat height so that handles/arm pads align with your shoulder joint / elbow height at start — ensures correct muscle alignment and joint mechanics.\n* Keep back fully against pad and core engaged — do not lean, arch, or use torso movement to lift; motion should come from shoulder abduction.\n* Maintain slight bend in elbows (if machine design allows) — avoids joint stress and focuses tension on delts rather than joints.\n* Lift and lower slowly — controlled tempo — avoid jerky movements or letting weight stack bang down; this ensures better muscle activation and reduces injury risk.\n* Use moderate weight over heavy — because this is a delt isolation exercise; heavy loads often shift work to traps or momentum, reducing isolation benefit and increasing joint stress.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "* Main target: The medial (lateral) head of the deltoid — responsible for abduction (lifting arms sideways), giving shoulder width/“cap” appearance.\n* Secondary / Supporting muscles: Anterior & posterior deltoid heads (to stabilize), upper-back stabilizers including trapezius and shoulder-blade muscles, and; rotator-cuff / scapular stabilizers to maintain shoulder alignment.",
      "benefits": "& Why Use Machine Lateral Raise\n* Strict isolation & form control: Since the machine stabilizes your posture and guides the motion, it reduces momentum and ensures that deltoids (not traps or momentum) do most of the work. Ideal for shoulder-width / shape routines.\n* Good for beginners or form-focused lifters: Easier to control than free weights (dumbbells), reduces technique demands — seat-pad and guided path make execution simpler and safer.\n* Constant tension through full range: Machine keeps load more consistent across movement, helping with hypertrophy and shoulder muscle activation.\n* Less involvement of stabilizers/back, more focus on delts: Because torso/back is supported, lower-body and core demand is reduced, letting shoulders take primary load — useful when wanting to isolate shoulders or if back/spine recovery is a concern.",
      "safety": "/ Technique Tips\n* Adjust seat height so that handles/arm pads align with your shoulder joint / elbow height at start — ensures correct muscle alignment and joint mechanics.\n* Keep back fully against pad and core engaged — do not lean, arch, or use torso movement to lift; motion should come from shoulder abduction.\n* Maintain slight bend in elbows (if machine design allows) — avoids joint stress and focuses tension on delts rather than joints.\n* Lift and lower slowly — controlled tempo — avoid jerky movements or letting weight stack bang down; this ensures better muscle activation and reduces injury risk.\n* Use moderate weight over heavy — because this is a delt isolation exercise; heavy loads often shift work to traps or momentum, reducing isolation benefit and increasing joint stress."
