      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult female, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "* Main target: The medial (lateral) head of the deltoid — responsible for abduction (lifting arms sideways), giving shoulder width/“cap” appearance.\n* Secondary / Supporting muscles: Anterior & posterior deltoid heads (to stabilize), upper-back stabilizers including trapezius and shoulder-blade muscles, and; rotator-cuff / scapular stabilizers to maintain shoulder alignment.",
      "benefits": "& Why Use Machine Lateral Raise\n* Strict isolation & form control: Since the machine stabilizes your posture and guides the motion, it reduces momentum and ensures that deltoids (not traps or momentum) do most of the work. Ideal for shoulder-width / shape routines.\n* Good for beginners or form-focused lifters: Easier to control than free weights (dumbbells), reduces technique demands — seat-pad and guided path make execution simpler and safer.\n* Constant tension through full range: Machine keeps load more consistent across movement, helping with hypertrophy and shoulder muscle activation.\n* Less involvement of stabilizers/back, more focus on delts: Because torso/back is supported, lower-body and core demand is reduced, letting shoulders take primary load — useful when wanting to isolate shoulders or if back/spine recovery is a concern.",
      "safety": "/ Technique Tips\n* Adjust seat height so that handles/arm pads align with your shoulder joint / elbow height at start — ensures correct muscle alignment and joint mechanics.\n* Keep back fully against pad and core engaged — do not lean, arch, or use torso movement to lift; motion should come from shoulder abduction.\n* Maintain slight bend in elbows (if machine design allows) — avoids joint stress and focuses tension on delts rather than joints.\n* Lift and lower slowly — controlled tempo — avoid jerky movements or letting weight stack bang down; this ensures better muscle activation and reduces injury risk.\n* Use moderate weight over heavy — because this is a delt isolation exercise; heavy loads often shift work to traps or momentum, reducing isolation benefit and increasing joint stress."
