      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional strength clip — approximately 7–9 seconds long.\n* Resolution: 1920 × 1080 (Full HD), 24 fps.\n* Lighting & Color: Gym or home-gym with neutral background (floor + landmine rig or bar in corner), soft key-light + ambient fill so shoulder, torso, and bar path are clearly visible.\n* Sound: Light ambient (barbell contact/slide, breath, minimal background noise), no voice-over (optional soft breath-in / breath-out cues).\nScene Setup\n* Equipment: Barbell placed in a landmine base (or wedged securely in corner), light-to-moderate weight plate(s) on free end.\n* Location: Floor/ground space in gym/home with enough clearance in front and above; stable floor surface.\n* Camera Setup: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low or waist-height) capturing from head to knees — to show torso alignment, kneeling stance, bar path, and arm movement.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, wearing training clothes (tank/tee + shorts or gym pants), positioned in half-kneeling stance, ready to press.\nAction / Beats (0 s–~8/9 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position: Subject kneels with one knee down (hip-width base), the other leg forefoot planted ahead for stability. Barbell end held with the arm on the side of the down-knee; the bar rests near shoulder level (in front of shoulder). Core tight, glute of down-side squeezed, torso upright, shoulders back and down.\n* 1–2 s — Brace & Prepare: Brace core and glutes, ensure spine is neutral, ribcage stacked over hips; keep eyes forward, shoulder blades stable, prevent excessive lumbar arching.\n* 2–4 s — Press / Concentric Phase: Exhale; press the barbell upward and slightly forward along its natural arc until arm is fully extended — wrist–elbow–shoulder aligned. Maintain torso upright, don’t lean back.\n* 4–5 s — Lockout / Hold: Pause ~0.2–0.5 s at full extension, shoulder stable, glutes/core tight; show upright posture and full lockout.\n* 5–7 s — Lower / Eccentric Phase: Inhale; control the bar back down to shoulder-level starting position, prevent torso collapse or pelvic shift; maintain core and glute tension.\n* 7–8/9 s — Reset / Ready: Back at start position, posture stable, ready for next rep or fade-out.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus (What Half-Kneeling Landmine Press Works)\n* Deltoids (shoulders) — especially anterior (front) and medial (side) heads, responsible for pressing motion and shoulder stability.\n* Triceps — for elbow extension at lockout.\n* Upper chest (clavicular portion of pectoralis major) — engaged due to the angled press trajectory, contributing to pushing power.\n* Core muscles (abs, obliques, spinal-stabilizers) — strong engagement required to resist rotation or torso collapse because the press is unilateral and stabilizing demand is high.\n* Glutes and hip stabilizers — especially glute on kneeling side, to stabilize pelvis and maintain upright posture.\n* Upper-back / scapular stabilizers (traps, serratus, rotator-cuff muscles) — to stabilize shoulder and maintain control through press and lockout.\nBenefits & Why Use Half-Kneeling Landmine Press\n* Shoulder-friendly overhead pressing: The angled bar path reduces joint stress compared to strict overhead press, making it safer for those with limited mobility or prior shoulder issues.\n* Core and torso stability development: Because you kneel and press unilaterally, your core and hips must stabilize dynamically — enhancing core strength and anti-rotation stability.\n* Lower-back friendly: Half-kneeling reduces lumbar load and arching, safer if you have back sensitivity or want overhead pressing without heavy spinal compression.\n* Unilateral strength / imbalance correction: Single-arm work helps identify and correct left-vs-right strength or stability imbalances.\n* Versatility and functional pressing pattern: The angled, “half horizontal + vertical” path works both pressing and pushing muscles with scapular mobility — a more functional movement than fixed-line presses.\nForm & Safety / Technique & Common Mistakes\n* Keep torso upright and spine neutral — don’t let your lower back arch or rib cage flare as you press. Engage core and glute on kneeling side.\n* Brace and stabilize hips properly — down-knee hip, front-shin vertical, pelvis aligned; this helps avoid torso rotation or imbalance.\n* Press along bar’s natural arc — upward and slightly forward, not strictly vertical; follow the bar path, don’t push across the body.\n* Use moderate load — because unilateral / kneeling press involves more stabilizers, heavy weight can compromise form or cause joint stress — start light.\n* Control both up and down phases — avoid jerky motion, uncontrolled descent, or relying on momentum.\n* Switch sides / arms evenly — perform balanced sets to avoid asymmetry, ensuring both sides get equal stability and strength work.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
